The paper deals with a speaker diarization system for STEM courses, which involves analyzing conversational turns and the number of participating students. This falls under the sub-category of Speech and Dialogue Processing (cs.SD). The paper also uses a modified form of Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) for iterative merging and re-segmentation, which is a common technique in machine learning and natural language processing (cs.CL). The paper also mentions unsupervised acoustic analysis, which is a sub-field of signal processing and machine learning (cs.SI). The paper also uses a novel dominance score, which is a form of data analysis and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper's focus on STEM courses and collaborative problem solving suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of Computer Science Education (cs.CE), although this is less likely than the other categories mentioned.
